1) Set up the problem with variables and initial conditions: at time 0 the band length is 3 in., the spider’s distance from the fixed end is 0 in., and the spider walks 1 in./min relative to the band.  

2) Observe that the band is lengthened by 3 in. every minute, so the length at the beginning of the (n + 1)-st minute is Lₙ = 3 + 3n.  

3) Because the band stretches uniformly during each minute, the fraction of the band the spider occupies is preserved while the band grows; therefore  
  Sₙ₊₁ = (Sₙ + 1) · (Lₙ₊₁ / Lₙ),  
where Sₙ is the spider’s distance from the rod at the start of minute n.  

4) Start with S₀ = 0, L₀ = 3 and apply the recurrence successively to get  
 n = 1: S₁ = 2;  
 n = 2: S₂ = 4.5;  
 n = 3: S₃ ≈ 7.333333;  
 n = 4: S₄ ≈ 10.416667;  
 n = 5: S₅ ≈ 13.7;  
 n = 6: S₆ ≈ 17.15;  
 n = 7: S₇ ≈ 20.742857;  
 n = 8: S₈ ≈ 24.460714;  
 n = 9: S₉ ≈ 28.28968;  
 n = 10: S₁₀ ≈ 32.21865.  

5) Note that after 10 minutes the band length is 33 in. and the spider is still short of the end (32.21865 in. < 33 in.).  

6) Let τ be the fraction of the 11th minute required for the spider to finish. During this minute the band length grows linearly from 33 in. to 36 in.: L(τ) = 33 + 3τ.  

7) In the same fraction of a minute, the spider moves τ in. relative to the band; his absolute position therefore is  
  S(τ) = (S₁₀ + τ) · (L(τ) / 33).  

8) Set S(τ) equal to L(τ) and solve for τ; the solution is τ ≈ 0.781355 min, giving a total travel time of 10 + 0.781355 = 10.781355 minutes for the spider to reach the end.

